  "prompt": "What were the terms to the Treaty of Versailles?",
  "response": "The Treaty of Versailles, signed on June 28, 1919, officially ended World War I between the Allied Powers and Germany. The treaty included several key terms and conditions, which can be summarized as follows:\n\n1. **Territorial Losses**: \n   - Germany lost significant territory, including Alsace-Lorraine to France, parts of Prussia to Poland (the Polish Corridor), and all of its overseas colonies.\n   - The Saar Basin was placed under the administration of the League of Nations for 15 years, after which a plebiscite would determine its future.\n   - The city of Danzig (now Gda\u0144sk, Poland) was declared a Free City.\n\n2. **Military Restrictions**: \n   - The size of the German army was limited to 100,000 troops.\n   - Germany was prohibited from having an air force and was restricted in terms of naval forces (limited to a small navy and no submarines).\n   - The Rhineland was demilitarized, meaning no German military forces were allowed in this region bordering France.\n\n3. **War Guilt Clause**: \n   - Article 231, known as the \"war guilt clause,\" placed full responsibility for the war on Germany and its allies, which served as the basis for reparations.\n\n4. **Reparations**: \n   - Germany was required to pay reparations for the damage caused during the war. The exact amount was determined later but was set at 132 billion gold marks (approximately $33 billion at the time).\n\n5. **League of Nations**: \n   - The Treaty established the League of Nations, an international organization aimed at promoting peace and preventing future conflicts. Germany was initially excluded from the League.\n\n6. **Colonial Mandates**: \n   - German territories in Africa and the Pacific were redistributed among the Allied Powers as mandates, essentially placing them under international control rather than outright annexation.\n\nThese terms were highly controversial and contributed to significant political and economic turmoil in Germany during the interwar years, ultimately leading to World War II. The treaty was viewed by many in Germany as a \"Diktat,\" or imposed peace, and remains a subject of historical debate regarding its fairness and impact.",
